Here's how to implement all three pieces:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation with a confirmation dialog**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        // Fire-and-forget since the override is synchronous
        Dispatcher.Dispatch(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        });

        return true; // Cancel the default navigation
    }
}
```

> **Note:** `OnBackButtonPressed` only fires for the **hardware/Android back button**. It does *not* fire when the user taps the Shell navigation bar back arrow.

**3. Replace the Shell back arrow with a custom "Cancel" toolbar item**

Hide the default back button and add your own:

```csharp
// In your constructor or OnAppearing
Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
{
    IsVisible = false // Hide default back arrow
});
```

Then in XAML, add a toolbar item:

```xml
<ContentPage.ToolbarItems>
    <ToolbarItem Text="Cancel" Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
</ContentPage.ToolbarItems>
```

Wire up the command (or use code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }

    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `return true` from `OnBackButtonPressed` cancels the default navigation.
- The `Dispatcher.Dispatch` pattern is needed because the override is synchronous but `DisplayAlert` is async.
- `BackButtonBehavior.IsVisible = false` hides the shell-provided arrow so your "Cancel" toolbar item is the only way back.
